{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0e3aeab5-27ba-4ce0-9002-8ab555fea0ca","content":"## What Happened\n\nC# 14 introduces **first-class implicit span conversions**. `T[]` now implicitly converts to `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, and this conversion is *preferred* by overload resolution over `T[]` → `IEnumerable<T>`.\n\nSo `array.Contains(num)` now binds to:\n```\nMemoryExtensions.Contains<int>(ReadOnlySpan<int>, int)\n```\ninstead of the old:\n```\nEnumerable.Contains<int>(IEnumerable<int>, int)\n```\n\nSince `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a **ref struct**, it cannot be represented in expression trees — the interpreter blows up at runtime when it encounters the method call.\n\n## Fix\n\nDisambiguate so the compiler selects `Enumerable.Contains`:\n\n**Option A** — cast the receiver:\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);\n```\n\n**Option B** — call the static method explicitly:\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);\n```\n\nEither restores the `IEnumerable<T>` overload, which expression trees (and the interpreter) support.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f7c91e27-24eb-4412-9a6e-1aed37cdc033","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change in .NET 10 / C# 14 that affects LINQ expression trees calling `.Contains()` on `int[]` arrays, specifically when using `Compile(preferInterpretation: true)`.\n\nLet me think about what changed in .NET 10 / C# 14 that would cause this.\n\nIn C# 14 / .NET 10, there's a significant change related to extension members. C# 14 introduces **extension types** (formerly \"roles and extensions\"), but more relevantly, there's a change in how the compiler resolves `Contains` on arrays.\n\nActually, let me think more carefully. \n\nI think the issue is that in .NET 10, the compiler's method resolution changed so that `MemoryExtensions.Contains` on `Span<T>` now takes priori